<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<Page x:Class="HamNetProgrammer.Desktop.Views.HelpPage"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      Background="#10161d">

    <ScrollViewer>
        <StackPanel Padding="16" Spacing="14" MaxWidth="900">

            <TextBlock Text="Help" FontSize="22" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#e0924a" />
            <TextBlock Text="What each screen does." FontSize="12" Foreground="#8896a0" />

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16" BorderBrush="#ffb74d" BorderThickness="1">
                <StackPanel Spacing="10">
                    <TextBlock Text="Support" FontSize="16" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#ffb74d" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#dddddd" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        HamNetProgrammer is a free, open-source codeplug tool for the AnyTone
                        AT-D878UV. It stores your whole codeplug in an open SQLite database, so
                        Zones, Scan Lists, Group Lists and Roaming Zones stay linked by identity
                        and survive reorganizing your channels. If it's useful to you, the
                        Support button funds continued development - and Follow us on Facebook
                        for updates on this and the other tools in the same series (PacketCluster/
                        Ham Net Global, SOARC Globe).
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Zones" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Create, rename and delete zones, add or remove channels, and reorder
                        them. Edit any channel's full field set, with a searchable talkgroup
                        picker that can create a new talkgroup on the fly. A channel's Scan List/
                        Group List fields here are a per-channel property (which list activates
                        when you scan or receive on THIS channel) - not the same thing as list
                        membership, which is edited on the Scan Lists/Group Lists pages themselves.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Channels" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Every channel across all zones in one list, independent of zone - search,
                        edit, or delete any channel outright (not just remove it from one zone),
                        and filter to channels that aren't in any zone at all. "New Channel..."
                        here creates a blank channel with no zone to inherit settings from; adding
                        it to a zone afterwards is a separate step (Add Existing Channel on the
                        Zones page).
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Scan Lists, Group Lists &amp; Roaming" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Each is independently editable, the same way Zones are. Scan Lists also
                        have their own priority-channel, look-back, dropout and dwell settings.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Contacts" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        The Talkgroups / My Contacts toggle switches what the search box searches:
                        talkgroups (searched live across all three networks - Brandmeister, TGIF,
                        FreeDMR - with a filter to narrow to one), or your own individually-added
                        contacts (search radioid.net and add anyone by callsign or name). Only
                        FreeDMR refreshes into your local list automatically on app launch - the
                        network your hotspot actually uses, and all that gets synced to the radio,
                        to keep the on-device talkgroup list from growing large enough to freeze
                        its own browser (happened once before). Picking any search result, local or
                        not, adds just that one talkgroup. Either kind can be picked for a channel
                        from the channel editor.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Radio IDs" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Your own callsign(s) and DMR ID(s) - what a channel transmits with, if you
                        have more than one programmed. "Look Up from radioid.net" fills in the DMR
                        ID for you from your callsign, so you don't need to know it by heart. A
                        radio you've already read from will have these filled in automatically;
                        this page is for setting one up from scratch.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Lists" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Turns Scan Lists, Group Lists and Roaming Zones on or off as a whole - if a
                        feature is off here, it's not written to the radio at all, rather than
                        written empty. "Sync Lists with Zones" automatically derives Scan/Group
                        Lists and Roaming Zones from your current zone membership on every write,
                        instead of maintaining them by hand.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Radio Settings" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        GPS and APRS (Digital reporting via a DMR talkgroup). Most fields here are
                        written to the radio on the next Write Codeplug; any field labeled
                        "(not written to radio yet)" is saved for your own reference but
                        deliberately left alone on write - no independently-confirmed byte offset
                        exists for it yet, and this tool would rather leave a setting unwritten
                        than guess at an unverified flash location.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Radio" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Connects to the AT-D878UV over its USB programming cable.
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,4,0,0">
                        <Run Text="Write Codeplug to Radio" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#dce6ea" /> writes the current codeplug across several programming sessions, with live progress. The radio restarts itself several times during this - expected, not an error. A full memory backup is taken automatically just before, and again just after, so nothing is at risk without a way back.
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run Text="Backup Radio Memory" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#dce6ea" /> reads every known memory region to a timestamped file - safe, read-only, independent of writing.
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run Text="Contribute a Memory-Map Sample" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#dce6ea" /> is also read-only, but for radios this project has no hardware to validate against (anything other than the AT-D878UV) - it uploads a raw memory capture to help extend real support to that model.
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run Text="Restore Previous Codeplug" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#dce6ea" /> lets you pick from any past Write Codeplug run, not just the most recent, and writes back exactly what it overwrote using the automatic backup taken just before it. If that write never actually reached the radio, it instead takes a fresh dump and proves the radio still matches the pre-write backup byte-for-byte, rather than just assuming so.
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        <Run Text="Send Diagnostic Report" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#dce6ea" /> sends the automatic backup and a log of everything written for investigation, if something looks wrong after a write - no need to attach anything yourself.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="Credits" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        The AT-D878UV's USB protocol and memory layout aren't officially documented
                        by AnyTone. These open-source projects assisted in the development of this
                        application:
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="8,0,0,0">
                        <Run Text="&#8226; " /><Hyperlink NavigateUri="https://github.com/hmatuschek/qdmr"><Run Text="hmatuschek/qdmr" /></Hyperlink><Run Text=" - full-featured C++ codeplug editor covering AnyTone, TYT/Retevis, Radioddity and others; also the source for the MD-380-family DFU/TyT protocol and memory layout." />
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="8,0,0,0">
                        <Run Text="&#8226; " /><Hyperlink NavigateUri="https://github.com/reald/anytone-flash-tools"><Run Text="reald/anytone-flash-tools" /></Hyperlink><Run Text=" - Wireshark-derived protocol and memory layout notes, plus a Python radio emulator used for safe testing over a virtual COM port pair." />
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,6,0,0">
                        Talkgroup and DMR ID data comes from the Brandmeister, TGIF and FreeDMR
                        networks (merged and deduped server-side) and
                        <Hyperlink NavigateUri="https://radioid.net"><Run Text="radioid.net" /></Hyperlink>'s
                        public user database. Neither is affiliated with this project.
                    </TextBlock>
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,6,0,0">
                        Vibe coded by <Hyperlink NavigateUri="https://claude.com/claude-code"><Run Text="Claude" /></Hyperlink>, directed and hardware-tested by G0FQB.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Background="#1a232c" CornerRadius="8" Padding="16">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="License" FontSize="15" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#dce6ea" />
                    <TextBlock Foreground="#aabbc4" FontSize="13" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        HamNetProgrammer is free software, licensed under the GNU General Public
